✅ JavaScript Map
A Map is a built‑in JavaScript object used to store key–value pairs, where keys can be of any data type.

🔹 Why Map exists (Problem with Objects)
In plain objects ({}):
	• Keys are converted to strings
	• Limited flexibility

const obj = {};
obj[1] = "one";
obj["1"] = "one again";
console.log(obj); // { "1": "one again" }
👉 Keys collide

✅ Solution: Map

const map = new Map();
map.set(1, "number key");
map.set("1", "string key");
console.log(map.get(1));   // number key
console.log(map.get("1")); // string key
✔ Keys remain distinct

🔹 Key Features of Map
✅ Any key type (object, function, primitive)
✅ Maintains insertion order
✅ Iterable
✅ Has .size property
✅ Better performance for frequent additions/removals

🔹 Common Map Methods

const map = new Map();
map.set("name", "Raju");
map.set("role", "Engineer");
map.get("name");     // Raju
map.has("role");     // true
map.delete("role");  // removes entry
map.size;            // 1
map.clear();         // removes all

🔹 Iterating a Map

for (let [key, value] of map) {
  console.log(key, value);
}

map.forEach((value, key) => {
  console.log(key, value);
});

🔹 Object vs Map (Quick)
Feature	Object	Map
Key types	String / Symbol	Any
Order	Not guaranteed	Preserved
Iteration	Manual	Built‑in
Size	Manual	.size
Performance	Average	Better

🔹 Real‑World Use Cases
✅ Caching data
✅ Lookup tables
✅ Tracking user sessions
✅ Storing metadata
✅ When keys are objects

✅ Interview One‑Liner
	Map is a key–value collection where keys can be of any type and entries maintain insertion order.

