✅ JavaScript WeakMap
A WeakMap is a special key–value collection in JavaScript where keys must be objects, and those keys are held weakly, allowing automatic garbage collection.

🔹 What makes WeakMap special?
	If an object used as a key has no other references, JavaScript can remove it from memory automatically, along with its WeakMap entry.
✅ This helps prevent memory leaks

🔹 Basic Syntax
const weakMap = new WeakMap();

🔹 Keys Rule (Very Important)
✅ Keys → Objects only
❌ Not allowed → string, number, boolean, null, undefined

const obj = {};
weakMap.set(obj, "data"); // ✅ valid
weakMap.set("key", "value"); // ❌ TypeError

🔹 Common Methods
Method	Purpose
set(key, value)	Add data
get(key)	Retrieve data
has(key)	Check existence
delete(key)	Remove entry

let user = { name: "Raju" };
const wm = new WeakMap();
wm.set(user, "Admin");
console.log(wm.get(user)); // Admin

🔹 Garbage Collection Example (Core Concept ⭐)

let obj = { id: 1 };
const wm = new WeakMap();
wm.set(obj, "metadata");
obj = null; // reference removed
✅ The object is garbage‑collected
✅ The WeakMap entry is removed automatically
❌ You can’t detect when this happens

🔹 Why WeakMap Is NOT Iterable
WeakMap does NOT support:
	• forEach
	• keys()
	• values()
	• entries()
	• .size
👉 Allowing iteration would prevent garbage collection, so it’s intentionally disabled.

🔹 Map vs WeakMap (Quick)
Feature	Map	WeakMap
Key types	Any	Objects only
Garbage collection	❌ No	✅ Yes
Iterable	✅ Yes	❌ No
Size	✅ Yes	❌ No
Use case	General data	Memory‑safe metadata

🔹 Real‑World Use Cases
✅ Private Data (Encapsulation)

const privateData = new WeakMap();
class User {
  constructor(name) {
    privateData.set(this, { secret: "1234" });
    this.name = name;
  }
}
✅ DOM element metadata
✅ Caching objects safely
✅ Avoiding memory leaks in large apps

✅ Interview One‑Liner
	WeakMap stores object keys weakly, allowing automatic garbage collection when the key object is no longer referenced.

When to Use WeakMap ✅
✔ Object‑linked data
✔ Unknown object lifetime
✔ Memory‑safe design
When NOT to Use ❌
✘ When you need iteration
✘ When keys are primitives
✘ When you need size/count

