✅ JavaScript WeakSet
A WeakSet is a special kind of Set that stores only objects, and those objects are held weakly, meaning they can be automatically garbage‑collected.

🔹 What is a WeakSet?
	WeakSet stores objects only, and does NOT prevent them from being removed from memory.
✅ Helps avoid memory leaks
✅ Used for tracking objects without owning them

🔹 Key Rules (Very Important ⭐)
✔ Values must be objects
❌ Primitives are NOT allowed

const ws = new WeakSet();
ws.add({ name: "Raju" }); // ✅ allowed
ws.add(10);               // ❌ TypeError

🔹 Syntax
const weakSet = new WeakSet();

🔹 Available Methods
Method	Description
add(object)	Adds an object
has(object)	Checks existence
delete(object)	Removes object

let user = { id: 1 };
const ws = new WeakSet();
ws.add(user);
console.log(ws.has(user)); // true

🔹 Garbage Collection (Core Concept)

let obj = { data: "temp" };
const ws = new WeakSet();
ws.add(obj);
obj = null; // reference removed
✅ Object is garbage‑collected
✅ WeakSet entry disappears automatically
❌ You cannot detect when this happens

🔹 Why WeakSet Is NOT Iterable
WeakSet does NOT support:
	• forEach
	• keys()
	• values()
	• size
👉 Iteration would prevent garbage collection, so it’s intentionally disabled.

🔹 Set vs WeakSet
Feature	Set	WeakSet
Values	Any type	Objects only
Garbage collected	❌ No	✅ Yes
Iterable	✅ Yes	❌ No
Size	✅ Yes	❌ No
Use case	General unique values	Object tracking

🔹 Real‑World Use Cases
✅ Track objects without memory leaks

const visited = new WeakSet();
function visit(obj) {
  if (visited.has(obj)) return;
  visited.add(obj);
}
✅ DOM element tracking
✅ Caching temporary objects
✅ Marking processed objects

🧠 Memory Diagram
Object  ──► WeakSet
   ↑
(no other references)
→ Garbage Collector removes object
→ WeakSet cleans entry automatically


✅ Interview One‑Liner
	WeakSet stores objects weakly and allows automatic garbage collection when objects are no longer referenced.

✅ When to Use WeakSet
✔ Track object state
✔ Prevent memory leaks
✔ Object lifecycle‑based logic
❌ When NOT to Use
✘ Need iteration
✘ Need primitives
✘ Need size/count

