✅ JavaScript Set
A Set is a built‑in JavaScript collection used to store unique values (no duplicates allowed).

🔹 What is a Set?
	Set stores values where each value can occur only once.
	• Values can be any data type
	• Maintains insertion order
	• Automatically removes duplicates

🔹 Syntax
const set = new Set();
Or with initial values:

const set = new Set([1, 2, 2, 3, 4]);
console.log(set); // Set { 1, 2, 3, 4 }

🔹 Common Set Methods
Method	Purpose
add(value)	Adds a value
has(value)	Checks if value exists
delete(value)	Removes a value
clear()	Removes all values
size	Number of elements
Example

const set = new Set();
set.add(10);
set.add(20);
set.add(10); // ignored (duplicate)
console.log(set.size); // 2
console.log(set.has(20)); // true
set.delete(10);

🔹 Iterating a Set

for (let value of set) {
  console.log(value);
}

set.forEach(value => {
  console.log(value);
});

🔹 Set vs Array
Feature	Array	Set
Duplicates	✅ Allowed	❌ Not allowed
Search (has)	Slow	Fast
Order	Preserved	Preserved
Index access	✅ Yes	❌ No
✅ Convert Array → Set (remove duplicates):
const unique = [...new Set([1, 2, 2, 3])];

🔹 Set vs Map (Quick)
Feature	Set	Map
Stores	Values only	Key–value pairs
Uniqueness	Values unique	Keys unique
Use case	Unique items	Lookups

🔹 Real‑World Use Cases
✅ Remove duplicate values
✅ Track unique users / IDs
✅ Check existence efficiently
✅ Intersection & union operations
Example: Union of two sets

const a = new Set([1, 2, 3]);
const b = new Set([3, 4, 5]);
const union = new Set([...a, ...b]);
// {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}

✅ Interview One‑Liner
	Set is a collection of unique values that eliminates duplicates automatically.

When to Use Set ✅
✔ You need unique values
✔ Fast existence checks
✔ De‑duplication
When NOT to Use ❌
✘ You need key‑value pairs
✘ You need indexing by position

